title: For Sale:  Stoeger 2000, 26" synthetic 12ga
postcontent:
The Stoeger Model 2000 is licensed to use Benelli's Inertia Driven® operating system - the heart of the world's most prestigious and reliable autoloaders. The Stoeger Model 2000 is Inertia Driven® with only two moving parts in the bolt: the bolt body and the rotating locking head. Simplicity ensures reliability and the Model 2000 is quickly gaining a reputation as the most reliable semi-automatic on the market in its price range.
Unlike common gas-operated guns whose fore-ends conceal operating rods, pistons, O-rings, valves and other moving parts, the inertia recoil system is primarily contained inside the receiver. The results? A trimmer fore-end, better balance, more reliable operation and the ability to fire everything from light target ammunition to the heaviest waterfowl loads without adjustments. And because propellant gas isn't vented from the barrel into the operating system, Inertia Driven® guns like the Model 2000 stay cleaner, even after hundreds of shots. Even under the toughest conditions, your new Model 2000 will keep on firing! Reliability, versatility and value are what you expect in a semi-automatic shotgun and no other semi-automatic in its price range even compares to the Model 2000. 


Used lightly for one season (10 hunts or so), looks just like new.  These are in stores for much more than I'm asking here ($450ish).  I have the box, documents, and chokes that came with it new.  Get ready for ducks and geese!

The Stoeger Model 2000 is licensed to use Benelli's Inertia Driven® operating system - the heart of the world's most prestigious and reliable autoloaders. The Stoeger Model 2000 is Inertia Driven® with only two moving parts in the bolt: the bolt body and the rotating locking head. Simplicity ensures reliability and the Model 2000 is quickly gaining a reputation as the most reliable semi-automatic on the market in its price range.
Unlike common gas-operated guns whose fore-ends conceal operating rods, pistons, O-rings, valves and other moving parts, the inertia recoil system is primarily contained inside the receiver. The results? A trimmer fore-end, better balance, more reliable operation and the ability to fire everything from light target ammunition to the heaviest waterfowl loads without adjustments. And because propellant gas isn't vented from the barrel into the operating system, Inertia Driven® guns like the Model 2000 stay cleaner, even after hundreds of shots. Even under the toughest conditions, your new Model 2000 will keep on firing! Reliability, versatility and value are what you expect in a semi-automatic shotgun and no other semi-automatic in its price range even compares to the Model 2000.

title: For Sale:  Rare Boutet Dueling Pair of Pistols - Gold Accents, Armorers Marks, Flintlock, circa 1802
postcontent:
Fine cased pair of Nicholas Boutet dueling pistols...Boutet was the primary armorer to Napoleon and these percussion pistols are of that era.  Fluted octagonal barrels, gold accents at muzzle, in armorers stamps and at touch-holes.  Engraving on lock reads "Manuf'td Versailles", engraved buttplates, full walnut stocks.  

These are a matched pair of officers pistols.  No cracks, rust or damage to the pistols - look to be approximately .62 caliber...graded as "fine" condition by several renowned collectors.  These pistols were purchased by my grandfather at the Metropolitan Museum sale of 1953 or 1954.

Case is not original - seems to be a converted English bird gun case circa 1780...that said, the interior has been modified for the pistols, most likely in the early 1800s as often happened with French dueling sets imported to England.

Serious inquiries only - price may be somewhat negotiable...I am not interested in trades at this time.  Pictures for serious buyers upon request.

title: For Sale/Trade:  AR-15_A1 5.56 mm Pre-Ban
postcontent:
For Trade: AR-15_A1 5.56 mm Pre-Ban
Want a larger caliber (.308+) AR-10 in trade or a good cash offer so I can purchase one. I prefer Armalite, but there are many great gun manufacturers here in the USA.

Upper: Colt 20-inch barrel 1:9 twist w/ bayonet lug. Barrel marked "C MP Chrome Bore"; C for the manufacturer Colt, MP stamp means the barrel was magnafluxed and proofed, chrome bore and chamber. Bolt Carrier manufacturer stamp "Shield (8 sided octagon) and SE"; Smith Enterprise.

Lower: PWA (Pac West Arms, Milan, Ill.; this was the early LMT company I believe and Rock River Arms bought out PWA. From everything that I have heard they are excellent lowers!) 5.56mm Commando. This is a forged lower not cast. Serial# 11174. (PWA post-ban have a year prefix in the serial number. The serial # cutoff was 35222 for preban status).

Standard two point sling.
Has a new AR-16 cleaning kit (Small Arms Maintenance Equipment Case 8465-00-781-9564).
A1 stock w/ butt storage compartment.
Have one USA 30 round AR-15 .223 magazine by O'Kay Industries, Inc., New Britain, Conn.

This AR is in great shape and supreme working order. I had it fully serviced (new parts, fired & cleaned) by a gunsmith at Anderson's Gun Repair Shop here in Springfield, MO before putting it up for sale; new extractor spring & gas tube (had a dent in the tube which slowed the gas pressure).  I also run some 40 rounds through it and cleaned it. It was flawless.

I've had this same rifle (but fully auto - M16) issued to me during the latter part of the Vietnam conflict. I hate to part with this, but with the times as they are now I would prefer a much larger caliber for home defense. Not worried about whether or not you can hunt with it.

Let me know what you have and I'll see if we can come to an agreement.
